      "name": "Do all women with PCOS have irregular periods?",
      "acceptedAnswer": {
        "@type": "Answer",
        "text": "No. While irregular or absent periods are common (affecting 70-80% of PCOS patients), some women have regular cycles and still have PCOS. They might present with infertility, acne, hair loss, or weight gain instead. This is why bloodwork is diagnostic: elevated androgens (free testosterone, DHEA-S) and/or abnormal LH:FSH ratio confirm PCOS even with regular periods. Ultrasound alone (showing cysts) is not sufficient. Your blood tests tell the metabolic story."
      }
    },
