      "@type": "Question",
      "name": "Does metformin work for PCOS?",
      "acceptedAnswer": {
        "@type": "Answer",
        "text": "Yes, but only if your PCOS is driven by insulin resistance. Metformin improves insulin sensitivity, which reduces excess androgen production. Many women see regular periods, reduced acne, and improved fertility within 3-4 months. The limitation: if your PCOS is adrenal, inflammatory, or post-pill (not insulin-driven), metformin helps less. This is why classification matters. arq. tests your insulin, glucose, HOMA-IR, and other markers to determine if metformin is appropriate or if you need spironolactone, inositol, or a different approach."
      }
    },
    {
      "@type": "Question",
      "name": "Is inositol better than metformin?",
      "acceptedAnswer": {
        "@type": "Answer",
        "text": "Not better — different. Inositol (myo-inositol, 40:1 ratio with D-chiro-inositol) mimics the action of metformin without the side effects (GI upset, lactic acidosis risk). For insulin-resistant PCOS, inositol works well and is often used in India as a dietary supplement (no prescription needed). Some studies show equal efficacy to metformin for ovulation and metabolic markers. Many physicians combine both: metformin for faster insulin correction, inositol for sustained benefit and tolerability. Your physician tailors this based on your PCOS type and tolerance."
      }
    },
    {
      "@type": "Question",
      "name": "If I have PCOS, will I definitely struggle to get pregnant?",
      "acceptedAnswer": {
        "@type": "Answer",
        "text": "No. PCOS is the leading cause of anovulatory infertility (not ovulating), but it's highly treatable. With the right protocol — metabolic treatment (metformin/inositol), androgen suppression (spironolactone), and lifestyle changes — 70-80% of PCOS women regain regular ovulation and conceive naturally. Even those who need assisted fertility respond better with metabolic optimization first. Start treating PCOS 3-6 months before trying to conceive. By the time you're ready, your cycle should be regulated and metabolic markers improved. Fertility is achievable with PCOS — it just requires the right approach."
      }
