      "@type": "Question",
      "name": "Why do doctors just prescribe birth control for PCOS?",
      "acceptedAnswer": {
        "@type": "Answer",
        "text": "Because it's quick and suppresses symptoms (periods, acne, hirsutism). Birth control masks PCOS but doesn't treat the underlying insulin resistance or metabolic dysfunction. When you stop it, symptoms return. Many Indian gynecologists default to birth control because it's familiar, quick to prescribe, and keeps patients compliant. The problem: it delays real metabolic treatment. And if you want to conceive, birth control helps you — it actively worsens your chances. arq. uses birth control selectively (usually combined with metformin or spironolactone for concurrent symptom relief) but prioritizes treating the metabolic cause. Masking ≠ healing."
